    {
      "id": "MP8jEOJ4kZVUsx6a8Ja-H",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1315.1031812601727,
      "y": 2414.304146216314,
      "width": 3249.56,
      "height": 1160.39,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bi8",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 274007234,
      "version": 1242,
      "versionNonce": 469924674,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1781199503350,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "The communication lifecycle between a Worker Node and the Master\n\n  - Worker Node — the node that sends heartbeats and runs containers\n  - Master (Leader) — the active master managing the cluster\n  - Cluster State — the persistent cluster state (Raft FSM). Shown separately to make it clear when state is being read or written\n\n  ---\n  AUTO-JOIN (first heartbeat = node discovered)\n\n  There is no explicit join request. When the master receives the first heartbeat from an unknown node, it automatically:\n  1. Adds the node to the cluster state\n  2. Assigns it to the matching resource pool based on its CPU/RAM from the heartbeat data\n\n  ---\n  HEARTBEAT LOOP (every 5 seconds, UDP multicast)\n\n  These 2 steps repeat every 5 seconds for the entire lifetime of the node:\n\n  1. Heartbeat(address, total/used CPU & RAM, containers) — the node sends a UDP multicast packet with its current state: total and used CPU and RAM, its command address, and the list of running containers. No response is expected (fire and forget).\n  2. UpdateNodeFromHeartbeat(metrics + address) — the master receives the packet and updates the node metrics and address. The Scheduler and Load Balancer will use this data when choosing a node for a new container.\n\n  If this loop stops (node crashes, network failure), Fault Tolerance will notice that lastHeartbeat is no longer being updated -> 15s SUSPECT -> 30s DEAD -> reschedule containers.\n\n  ---\n  NODE REMOVAL\n\n  There is no explicit leave request. When a worker stops, it simply stops sending heartbeats.\n  The master detects the absence (15s SUSPECT, 30s DEAD) marks the node DEAD and reschedules its containers onto healthy nodes. The node entry stays DEAD until its heartbeats resume.\n",
      "fontSize": 23.802970227571212,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "The communication lifecycle between a Worker Node and the Master\n\n  - Worker Node — the node that sends heartbeats and runs containers\n  - Master (Leader) — the active master managing the cluster\n  - Cluster State — the persistent cluster state (Raft FSM). Shown separately to make it clear when state is being read or written\n\n  ---\n  AUTO-JOIN (first heartbeat = node discovered)\n\n  There is no explicit join request. When the master receives the first heartbeat from an unknown node, it automatically:\n  1. Adds the node to the cluster state\n  2. Assigns it to the matching resource pool based on its CPU/RAM from the heartbeat data\n\n  ---\n  HEARTBEAT LOOP (every 5 seconds, UDP multicast)\n\n  These 2 steps repeat every 5 seconds for the entire lifetime of the node:\n\n  1. Heartbeat(address, total/used CPU & RAM, containers) — the node sends a UDP multicast packet with its current state: total and used CPU and RAM, its command address, and the list of running containers. No response is expected (fire and forget).\n  2. UpdateNodeFromHeartbeat(metrics + address) — the master receives the packet and updates the node metrics and address. The Scheduler and Load Balancer will use this data when choosing a node for a new container.\n\n  If this loop stops (node crashes, network failure), Fault Tolerance will notice that lastHeartbeat is no longer being updated -> 15s SUSPECT -> 30s DEAD -> reschedule containers.\n\n  ---\n  NODE REMOVAL\n\n  There is no explicit leave request. When a worker stops, it simply stops sending heartbeats.\n  The master detects the absence (15s SUSPECT, 30s DEAD) marks the node DEAD and reschedules its containers onto healthy nodes. The node entry stays DEAD until its heartbeats resume.\n",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "1KjIzZ5tTNrMUwZa6SeS4",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1309.7751406940704,
      "y": 3622.202112632759,
      "width": 3146.99,
      "height": 1111.7,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bi9",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 5187742,
      "version": 388,
      "versionNonce": 362754818,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1781203020375,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "   Fault Tolerance: Detection & Recovery\n  \n  - Worker — the node that fails\n  - Fault Tolerance Manager — the master module that monitors heartbeats\n  - Scheduler + Load Balancer — combined into one participant; Scheduler filters eligible nodes, LB picks the best one\n  - Healthy Node — another worker in the cluster that is alive and has available resources\n\n  ---\n  FAILURE DETECTION\n\n  The node stops sending heartbeats (crash, network failure, power off). Fault Tolerance Manager periodically checks time.Now() - lastHeartbeat:\n\n  - 5s — 1 missed heartbeat. Normal, could be network jitter. No action.\n  - 10s — 2 missed heartbeats. Still no action, but getting suspicious.\n  - 15s — 3 missed heartbeats. Master marks the node SUSPECT. Doesn't reschedule yet, gives the node a chance to recover.\n  - 30s — 6 missed heartbeats. Master marks the node DEAD. Recovery begins.\n\n  ---\n  CONTAINER RECOVERY\n\n  The node is DEAD, but its services still need to run. The loop repeats for each container that was active on the dead node (stopped or failed containers are not recovered):\n\n  1. Reschedule(service) — Fault Tolerance asks the Scheduler to start a fresh container for this service\n  2. StartContainer(image, cpuLimit, ramLimit, envVars, ports, cmd) — Scheduler filters nodes in the matching pool with sufficient resources, LB picks the best one, and sends the start command with full service parameters\n  3. containerID (success) — the healthy node confirms the container was started\n  4. OK or status = PENDING (no resources) — two outcomes:\n    - OK — container successfully started\n    - PENDING — no node has enough resources. A retry loop on the leader tries again every 10 seconds; pending containers of the same service start only together\n\n  ---\n  SPLIT BRAIN PREVENTION\n\n  Scenario: the node wasn't actually dead, the network was temporarily down. After 30s it comes back and sends a heartbeat.\n\n  1. Late heartbeat arrives (node was DEAD) — the node tries to send a heartbeat as if nothing happened\n  2. KillContainers(nodeID) — the master sends a command to the recovered node to stop all its running containers. Why? Because those containers have already been rescheduled onto other healthy nodes. If the recovered node kept running them, there would be duplicates — the same containers running on both the recovered node and the nodes where they were rescheduled.\n\n  The node stays DEAD until the worker confirms the kill; only then is it brought back to ALIVE and made available for new scheduling. Only the leader sends the command. The worker finds its containers through Docker labels, so the cleanup works even if the worker process itself was restarted in the meantime.",
      "fontSize": 22.804171386453266,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "   Fault Tolerance: Detection & Recovery\n  \n  - Worker — the node that fails\n  - Fault Tolerance Manager — the master module that monitors heartbeats\n  - Scheduler + Load Balancer — combined into one participant; Scheduler filters eligible nodes, LB picks the best one\n  - Healthy Node — another worker in the cluster that is alive and has available resources\n\n  ---\n  FAILURE DETECTION\n\n  The node stops sending heartbeats (crash, network failure, power off). Fault Tolerance Manager periodically checks time.Now() - lastHeartbeat:\n\n  - 5s — 1 missed heartbeat. Normal, could be network jitter. No action.\n  - 10s — 2 missed heartbeats. Still no action, but getting suspicious.\n  - 15s — 3 missed heartbeats. Master marks the node SUSPECT. Doesn't reschedule yet, gives the node a chance to recover.\n  - 30s — 6 missed heartbeats. Master marks the node DEAD. Recovery begins.\n\n  ---\n  CONTAINER RECOVERY\n\n  The node is DEAD, but its services still need to run. The loop repeats for each container that was active on the dead node (stopped or failed containers are not recovered):\n\n  1. Reschedule(service) — Fault Tolerance asks the Scheduler to start a fresh container for this service\n  2. StartContainer(image, cpuLimit, ramLimit, envVars, ports, cmd) — Scheduler filters nodes in the matching pool with sufficient resources, LB picks the best one, and sends the start command with full service parameters\n  3. containerID (success) — the healthy node confirms the container was started\n  4. OK or status = PENDING (no resources) — two outcomes:\n    - OK — container successfully started\n    - PENDING — no node has enough resources. A retry loop on the leader tries again every 10 seconds; pending containers of the same service start only together\n\n  ---\n  SPLIT BRAIN PREVENTION\n\n  Scenario: the node wasn't actually dead, the network was temporarily down. After 30s it comes back and sends a heartbeat.\n\n  1. Late heartbeat arrives (node was DEAD) — the node tries to send a heartbeat as if nothing happened\n  2. KillContainers(nodeID) — the master sends a command to the recovered node to stop all its running containers. Why? Because those containers have already been rescheduled onto other healthy nodes. If the recovered node kept running them, there would be duplicates — the same containers running on both the recovered node and the nodes where they were rescheduled.\n\n  The node stays DEAD until the worker confirms the kill; only then is it brought back to ALIVE and made available for new scheduling. Only the leader sends the command. The worker finds its containers through Docker labels, so the cleanup works even if the worker process itself was restarted in the meantime.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "9yXg8LSMyh8ZWfaec5DKB",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1301.7734355816924,
      "y": 4785.014659920534,
      "width": 2922.94,
      "height": 995.91,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "biA",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 677423006,
      "version": 376,
      "versionNonce": 1417424926,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1781203020375,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "  Service Deployment Flow\n\n  - User — the user deploying a service\n  - REST API — the platform's entry point\n  - Security — authentication and authorization module\n  - Scheduler — decides where containers run\n  - Load Balancer — picks the specific node from the candidate list\n  - Worker — the node that will run the container\n\n  ---\n  AUTHENTICATION & AUTHORIZATION\n\n  1. POST /services {image, cpu, ram, replicas, pool, envVars, ports, cmd} Authorization: Bearer <JWT> — the user sends an HTTP request with service parameters. The JWT token is included in the header.\n  2. Authenticate(token) — the API passes the token to Security. Security verifies the digital signature and expiration.\n  3. Authorize(user, service:create) — Security extracts the role from the token and checks the ACL to see if that role can perform the requested action. service:create is the permission needed for deploy.\n  4. OK — role: writer — authorization confirmed. If the user had been a Reader, the response would be 403 Forbidden and the flow would stop here.\n\n  ---\n  CONTAINER SCHEDULING (per replica)\n\n  The Scheduler first plans ALL replicas at once (all-or-nothing): the resources and ports taken by each replica are subtracted before placing the next one, and if any replica cannot be placed, nothing starts — all replicas are created PENDING and the retry loop starts the whole group later. If the user requested 3 replicas, the planning loop executes 3 times:\n\n  1. Schedule(service) — the API asks the Scheduler to find a node for one replica\n  2. Filter pool nodes with enough CPU & RAM — the Scheduler takes the list of nodes in the requested pool and filters out nodes that are not ALIVE, lack CPU or RAM, or already use one of the requested ports. If the service requires 0.5\n  CPU and a node only has 0.1 CPU free, that node is eliminated.\n  3. SelectNode(candidates) — the Scheduler passes the candidate list to LB\n  4. Load Balancer — applies the chosen strategy:\n    - LeastConnections — picks the node with the fewest running containers\n    - Weighted — calculates a score based on available CPU and RAM, picks the node with the highest score\n    - The strategy is pluggable — can be swapped without modifying the rest of the code\n  5. selectedNode — LB returns the chosen node\n  6. StartContainer(image, cpuLimit, ramLimit, envVars, ports, cmd) — the Scheduler sends the start command to the chosen node, including the Docker image, resource limits, and service parameters\n  7. containerID — the Worker starts the container via Docker Engine and returns the ID\n\n  Final response\n\n  After the loop completes (all replicas have been scheduled):\n\n  201 Created {serviceID, containers[]} — the user receives the service ID and the list of created containers with their locations.\n",
      "fontSize": 19.918279937270768,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "  Service Deployment Flow\n\n  - User — the user deploying a service\n  - REST API — the platform's entry point\n  - Security — authentication and authorization module\n  - Scheduler — decides where containers run\n  - Load Balancer — picks the specific node from the candidate list\n  - Worker — the node that will run the container\n\n  ---\n  AUTHENTICATION & AUTHORIZATION\n\n  1. POST /services {image, cpu, ram, replicas, pool, envVars, ports, cmd} Authorization: Bearer <JWT> — the user sends an HTTP request with service parameters. The JWT token is included in the header.\n  2. Authenticate(token) — the API passes the token to Security. Security verifies the digital signature and expiration.\n  3. Authorize(user, service:create) — Security extracts the role from the token and checks the ACL to see if that role can perform the requested action. service:create is the permission needed for deploy.\n  4. OK — role: writer — authorization confirmed. If the user had been a Reader, the response would be 403 Forbidden and the flow would stop here.\n\n  ---\n  CONTAINER SCHEDULING (per replica)\n\n  The Scheduler first plans ALL replicas at once (all-or-nothing): the resources and ports taken by each replica are subtracted before placing the next one, and if any replica cannot be placed, nothing starts — all replicas are created PENDING and the retry loop starts the whole group later. If the user requested 3 replicas, the planning loop executes 3 times:\n\n  1. Schedule(service) — the API asks the Scheduler to find a node for one replica\n  2. Filter pool nodes with enough CPU & RAM — the Scheduler takes the list of nodes in the requested pool and filters out nodes that are not ALIVE, lack CPU or RAM, or already use one of the requested ports. If the service requires 0.5\n  CPU and a node only has 0.1 CPU free, that node is eliminated.\n  3. SelectNode(candidates) — the Scheduler passes the candidate list to LB\n  4. Load Balancer — applies the chosen strategy:\n    - LeastConnections — picks the node with the fewest running containers\n    - Weighted — calculates a score based on available CPU and RAM, picks the node with the highest score\n    - The strategy is pluggable — can be swapped without modifying the rest of the code\n  5. selectedNode — LB returns the chosen node\n  6. StartContainer(image, cpuLimit, ramLimit, envVars, ports, cmd) — the Scheduler sends the start command to the chosen node, including the Docker image, resource limits, and service parameters\n  7. containerID — the Worker starts the container via Docker Engine and returns the ID\n\n  Final response\n\n  After the loop completes (all replicas have been scheduled):\n\n  201 Created {serviceID, containers[]} — the user receives the service ID and the list of created containers with their locations.\n",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "7_SGlr8OhfwCx6kDopalW",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1295.959616545514,
      "y": 5890.710590014836,
      "width": 2241.1212796720224,
      "height": 1200,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "biB",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2021514078,
      "version": 130,
      "versionNonce": 2074750018,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773824838850,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "  Leader Election / Raft Consensus\n\n  - Master 1 (Leader) — the active master processing all requests\n  - Master 2 (Follower) — passive replica, only receives data from the leader\n  - Master 3 (Follower) — another passive replica\n\n  There are physically 3 instances, but only one is active at any time. The other 2 just replicate state and wait.\n\n  ---\n  Section 1 — NORMAL OPERATION (Log Replication)\n\n  How the cluster works when everything is OK:\n\n  1. AppendEntries(term, entries) — the leader sends every state change (node added, service created, container started) to Master 2.\n  2. Success — Master 2 confirms it saved the data.\n  3. AppendEntries(term, entries) — the same data goes to Master 3.\n  4. Success — Master 3 confirms.\n\n  This is the replication mechanism. Every decision is saved on all 3 nodes. If the leader dies, the state is not lost — the other 2 have identical copies.\n\n  ---\n  CRASHES\n\n  Master 1 stops (crash, power off, network failure). It stops sending AppendEntries and stops responding.\n\n  ---\n  ELECTION PHASE\n\n  Master 2 and Master 3 notice they're no longer receiving heartbeats from the leader. After an election timeout (150-300ms, randomized), one of them initiates an election:\n\n  1. Master 2: Become CANDIDATE, vote for self — Master 2 proposes itself as leader. It increments its term and votes for itself. It already has 1 vote out of 3.\n  2. Master 2 → Master 3: RequestVote(term, lastLogIndex) — asks Master 3 for its vote. Sends the new term and the index of the last log entry (so Master 3 can verify that Master 2 has up-to-date data).\n  3. Master 3 → Master 2: VoteGranted(term) — Master 3 grants its vote. Now Master 2 has 2 votes out of 3 = majority.\n  4. Master 2: Majority (2/3) → NEW LEADER — Master 2 becomes the new leader.\n  5. Master 2 → Master 3: Heartbeat (new term) — the new leader immediately sends a heartbeat with the new term, announcing to everyone: \"I am the leader now\". From this point on, Master 2 processes requests\n  and sends AppendEntries.\n\n  ---\n  OLD LEADER RECOVERS\n\n  Master 1 comes back online (restarted, network restored). It doesn't know it's been replaced:\n\n  1. AppendEntries(old term) — Master 1 tries to send data with the old term, thinking it's still the leader.\n  2. Reject(higher term) — Master 2 rejects the message and tells it: \"my term is higher than yours, so I am the leader now.\"\n  3. Master 1 understands the situation, gives up the leader role and becomes a follower. From now on it will receive AppendEntries from Master 2 and sync its state.\n\n  This mechanism guarantees that two leaders can never exist simultaneously. The higher term always wins.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "  Leader Election / Raft Consensus\n\n  - Master 1 (Leader) — the active master processing all requests\n  - Master 2 (Follower) — passive replica, only receives data from the leader\n  - Master 3 (Follower) — another passive replica\n\n  There are physically 3 instances, but only one is active at any time. The other 2 just replicate state and wait.\n\n  ---\n  Section 1 — NORMAL OPERATION (Log Replication)\n\n  How the cluster works when everything is OK:\n\n  1. AppendEntries(term, entries) — the leader sends every state change (node added, service created, container started) to Master 2.\n  2. Success — Master 2 confirms it saved the data.\n  3. AppendEntries(term, entries) — the same data goes to Master 3.\n  4. Success — Master 3 confirms.\n\n  This is the replication mechanism. Every decision is saved on all 3 nodes. If the leader dies, the state is not lost — the other 2 have identical copies.\n\n  ---\n  CRASHES\n\n  Master 1 stops (crash, power off, network failure). It stops sending AppendEntries and stops responding.\n\n  ---\n  ELECTION PHASE\n\n  Master 2 and Master 3 notice they're no longer receiving heartbeats from the leader. After an election timeout (150-300ms, randomized), one of them initiates an election:\n\n  1. Master 2: Become CANDIDATE, vote for self — Master 2 proposes itself as leader. It increments its term and votes for itself. It already has 1 vote out of 3.\n  2. Master 2 → Master 3: RequestVote(term, lastLogIndex) — asks Master 3 for its vote. Sends the new term and the index of the last log entry (so Master 3 can verify that Master 2 has up-to-date data).\n  3. Master 3 → Master 2: VoteGranted(term) — Master 3 grants its vote. Now Master 2 has 2 votes out of 3 = majority.\n  4. Master 2: Majority (2/3) → NEW LEADER — Master 2 becomes the new leader.\n  5. Master 2 → Master 3: Heartbeat (new term) — the new leader immediately sends a heartbeat with the new term, announcing to everyone: \"I am the leader now\". From this point on, Master 2 processes requests\n  and sends AppendEntries.\n\n  ---\n  OLD LEADER RECOVERS\n\n  Master 1 comes back online (restarted, network restored). It doesn't know it's been replaced:\n\n  1. AppendEntries(old term) — Master 1 tries to send data with the old term, thinking it's still the leader.\n  2. Reject(higher term) — Master 2 rejects the message and tells it: \"my term is higher than yours, so I am the leader now.\"\n  3. Master 1 understands the situation, gives up the leader role and becomes a follower. From now on it will receive AppendEntries from Master 2 and sync its state.\n\n  This mechanism guarantees that two leaders can never exist simultaneously. The higher term always wins.\n",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "8hgi2iI2idayOU2u81SFz",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1293.3677689017918,
      "y": 7155.199441730071,
      "width": 3050.82,
      "height": 756.94,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "biC",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1257961154,
      "version": 243,
      "versionNonce": 769034562,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1781199487989,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "  Worker Node State Machine \n\n  ALIVE — the initial and normal state. A node enters this state when the master receives its first heartbeat (auto-join). Sends a heartbeat every 5s. It runs containers and is available for scheduling.\n  SUSPECT — the master hasn't received a heartbeat from the node for 15 seconds. Something is probably wrong, but it's not certain — it could be a temporary network lag. The master doesn't act yet, just marks the node.\n  DEAD — the master hasn't received a heartbeat for 30 seconds. The node is considered dead. The master starts fresh containers on other nodes using the original service parameters.\n  REMOVED — a reserved final state for a node fully taken out of the cluster. In the current implementation a dead node stays DEAD; automatic cleanup to REMOVED is future work.\n\n  Transitions (what causes state changes)\n\n  - First heartbeat received — the master discovers the node and adds it to the cluster (auto-join)\n  - Heartbeat OK every 5s — self-loop, the node keeps confirming it's alive\n  - No heartbeat for 15s — 3 consecutive missed heartbeats\n  - Heartbeat resumed — the node comes back and sends a heartbeat. Everything is OK, state is restored\n  - No heartbeat for 30s — still no heartbeat. The node is declared dead\n  - Late heartbeat — a DEAD node that sends heartbeats again is brought back to ALIVE after its old containers are confirmed killed\n\n  When a node stops sending heartbeats (crash, shutdown, network failure), the master detects it, marks it DEAD and reschedules its containers onto healthy nodes.",
      "fontSize": 21.62694714561143,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "  Worker Node State Machine \n\n  ALIVE — the initial and normal state. A node enters this state when the master receives its first heartbeat (auto-join). Sends a heartbeat every 5s. It runs containers and is available for scheduling.\n  SUSPECT — the master hasn't received a heartbeat from the node for 15 seconds. Something is probably wrong, but it's not certain — it could be a temporary network lag. The master doesn't act yet, just marks the node.\n  DEAD — the master hasn't received a heartbeat for 30 seconds. The node is considered dead. The master starts fresh containers on other nodes using the original service parameters.\n  REMOVED — a reserved final state for a node fully taken out of the cluster. In the current implementation a dead node stays DEAD; automatic cleanup to REMOVED is future work.\n\n  Transitions (what causes state changes)\n\n  - First heartbeat received — the master discovers the node and adds it to the cluster (auto-join)\n  - Heartbeat OK every 5s — self-loop, the node keeps confirming it's alive\n  - No heartbeat for 15s — 3 consecutive missed heartbeats\n  - Heartbeat resumed — the node comes back and sends a heartbeat. Everything is OK, state is restored\n  - No heartbeat for 30s — still no heartbeat. The node is declared dead\n  - Late heartbeat — a DEAD node that sends heartbeats again is brought back to ALIVE after its old containers are confirmed killed\n\n  When a node stops sending heartbeats (crash, shutdown, network failure), the master detects it, marks it DEAD and reschedules its containers onto healthy nodes.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "r2gIdlhzqH-sNN4y5IIhO",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1295.9194568534504,
      "y": 7986.918441598625,
