      "updated": 1781199487989,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": " Security & Audit Architecture\n\n  Trusted Network (Node <-> Master)\n\n  All nodes run within a trusted internal network (private datacenter, isolated VLAN). No TLS encryption is needed for node-to-master communication:\n\n  1. Worker sends first heartbeat (UDP multicast) — the master discovers the node automatically\n  2. Master discovers node automatically — adds it to cluster state\n  3. Assigns node to pool by CPU/RAM — based on the resources reported in the heartbeat\n  4. All communication over trusted network — heartbeats via UDP multicast, commands (StartContainer, KillContainers) via TCP\n  5. Heartbeat UDP, commands TCP (no TLS) — no encryption overhead, the network perimeter provides security\n\n  JWT\n\n  How users authenticate:\n\n  1. User authenticates (username + password) — the user sends credentials to a login endpoint\n  2. API returns signed JWT tokens — the API generates a signed access token (15 min) and a refresh token (24 h). \n  3. Token payload: {userID, role, type, expiration} — the token contains who you are, what role you have, the token type (access or refresh), and when it expires. This data is encoded in the token, no database lookup needed on each request\n  4. Each request: Authorization: Bearer  — on every subsequent request, the user puts the token in the HTTP header\n  5. API validates signature + checks expiry — the API checks two things: the signature is valid (token wasn't modified) and the token hasn't expired\n\n  ACL (Role-Based Access Control)\n\n  The 3 roles and what each can do:\n\n  - ADMIN — full access: manage nodes, services, pools, users, read audit. The platform administrator.\n  - WRITER — can deploy and delete services. Can view nodes and pools. Cannot manage users or nodes. The developer running their applications.\n  - READER — read-only: views services, nodes, pools, audit logs. Cannot modify anything. For monitoring or stakeholders who want to see system status.\n\n  How it works: on each request, Security extracts the role from the JWT, checks the ACL table to see if that role has permission for the requested action. If not → 403 Forbidden.\n\n  Audit Log (Append-Only)\n\n  What gets logged and how:\n\n  Events tracked:\n  - NODE_DISCOVERED / NODE_DEAD — when a new node is discovered via first heartbeat, or when a node dies\n  - SERVICE_CREATE / SERVICE_DELETE — when a service is created or deleted\n  - CONTAINER_RESCHEDULED — when a container is moved to another node (fault tolerance)\n  - AUTH_DENIED / LOGIN — when a user is denied permission or logs in\n  - LOGIN — when a user authenticates\n\n  Properties:\n  - Storage: append-only on master nodes — the log is only appended to, never modified or deleted. \n  - Query: GET /audit?action=...&user=... — API for querying. You can filter by action type and user\n  - Storage: in memory, per master — the audit log lives in the in-memory cluster state and is not replicated through Raft (durable, replicated audit is future work)\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": " Security & Audit Architecture\n\n  Trusted Network (Node <-> Master)\n\n  All nodes run within a trusted internal network (private datacenter, isolated VLAN). No TLS encryption is needed for node-to-master communication:\n\n  1. Worker sends first heartbeat (UDP multicast) — the master discovers the node automatically\n  2. Master discovers node automatically — adds it to cluster state\n  3. Assigns node to pool by CPU/RAM — based on the resources reported in the heartbeat\n  4. All communication over trusted network — heartbeats via UDP multicast, commands (StartContainer, KillContainers) via TCP\n  5. Heartbeat UDP, commands TCP (no TLS) — no encryption overhead, the network perimeter provides security\n\n  JWT\n\n  How users authenticate:\n\n  1. User authenticates (username + password) — the user sends credentials to a login endpoint\n  2. API returns signed JWT tokens — the API generates a signed access token (15 min) and a refresh token (24 h). \n  3. Token payload: {userID, role, type, expiration} — the token contains who you are, what role you have, the token type (access or refresh), and when it expires. This data is encoded in the token, no database lookup needed on each request\n  4. Each request: Authorization: Bearer  — on every subsequent request, the user puts the token in the HTTP header\n  5. API validates signature + checks expiry — the API checks two things: the signature is valid (token wasn't modified) and the token hasn't expired\n\n  ACL (Role-Based Access Control)\n\n  The 3 roles and what each can do:\n\n  - ADMIN — full access: manage nodes, services, pools, users, read audit. The platform administrator.\n  - WRITER — can deploy and delete services. Can view nodes and pools. Cannot manage users or nodes. The developer running their applications.\n  - READER — read-only: views services, nodes, pools, audit logs. Cannot modify anything. For monitoring or stakeholders who want to see system status.\n\n  How it works: on each request, Security extracts the role from the JWT, checks the ACL table to see if that role has permission for the requested action. If not → 403 Forbidden.\n\n  Audit Log (Append-Only)\n\n  What gets logged and how:\n\n  Events tracked:\n  - NODE_DISCOVERED / NODE_DEAD — when a new node is discovered via first heartbeat, or when a node dies\n  - SERVICE_CREATE / SERVICE_DELETE — when a service is created or deleted\n  - CONTAINER_RESCHEDULED — when a container is moved to another node (fault tolerance)\n  - AUTH_DENIED / LOGIN — when a user is denied permission or logs in\n  - LOGIN — when a user authenticates\n\n  Properties:\n  - Storage: append-only on master nodes — the log is only appended to, never modified or deleted. \n  - Query: GET /audit?action=...&user=... — API for querying. You can filter by action type and user\n  - Storage: in memory, per master — the audit log lives in the in-memory cluster state and is not replicated through Raft (durable, replicated audit is future work)\n",
